Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.710 --> 00:00:05.576
Professor Ben Polak:
Okay, so last time we looked at

00:00:05.576 --> 00:00:08.805
and played this game.
You had to choose grades,

00:00:08.805 --> 00:00:12.740
so you had to choose Alpha and
Beta, and this table told us

00:00:12.740 --> 00:00:15.410
what outcome would arise.
In particular,

00:00:15.410 --> 00:00:18.770
what grade you would get and
what grade your pair would get.

00:00:18.770 --> 00:00:21.771
So, for example,
if you had chosen Beta and your

00:00:21.771 --> 00:00:25.157
pair had chosen Alpha,
then you would get a C and your

00:00:25.157 --> 00:00:28.152
pair would get an A.
One of the first things we

00:00:28.152 --> 00:00:31.020
pointed out, is that this is not
quite a game yet.

00:00:31.020 --> 00:00:35.319
It's missing something.
This has outcomes in it,

00:00:35.319 --> 00:00:40.533
it's an outcome matrix,
but it isn't a game,

00:00:40.533 --> 00:00:46.110
because for a game we need to
know payoffs.

00:00:46.110 --> 00:00:49.390
Then we looked at some possible
payoffs, and now it is a game.

00:00:49.390 --> 00:00:51.888
So this is a game,
just to give you some more

00:00:51.888 --> 00:00:53.990
jargon, this is a normal-form
game.

00:00:53.990 --> 00:00:57.442
And here we've assumed the
payoffs are those that arise if

00:00:57.442 --> 00:01:00.955
players only care about their
own grades, which I think was

00:01:00.955 --> 00:01:03.583
true for a lot of you.
It wasn't true for the

00:01:03.583 --> 00:01:06.407
gentleman who's sitting there
now, but it was true for a lot

00:01:06.407 --> 00:01:08.033
of people.
We pointed out,

00:01:08.033 --> 00:01:11.380
that in this game,
Alpha strictly dominates Beta.

00:01:11.380 --> 00:01:14.694
What do we mean by that?
We mean that if these are your

00:01:14.694 --> 00:01:18.993
payoffs, no matter what your
pair does, you attain a higher

00:01:18.993 --> 00:01:23.590
payoff from choosing Alpha,
than you do from choosing Beta.

00:01:23.590 --> 00:01:26.031
Let's focus on a couple of
lessons of the class before I

00:01:26.031 --> 00:01:28.365
come back to this.
One lesson was,

00:01:28.365 --> 00:01:32.510
do not play a strictly
dominated strategy.

00:01:32.510 --> 00:01:35.150
Everybody remember that lesson?
Then much later on,

00:01:35.150 --> 00:01:37.852
when we looked at some more
complicated payoffs and a more

00:01:37.852 --> 00:01:40.989
complicated game,
we looked at a different lesson

00:01:40.989 --> 00:01:44.098
which was this:
put yourself in others' shoes

00:01:44.098 --> 00:01:47.629
to try and figure out what
they're going to do.

00:01:47.629 --> 00:01:49.581
So in fact, what we learned
from that is,

00:01:49.581 --> 00:01:52.166
it doesn't just matter what
your payoffs are -- that's

00:01:52.166 --> 00:01:55.141
obviously important -- it's also
important what other people's

00:01:55.141 --> 00:01:57.543
payoffs are,
because you want to try and

00:01:57.543 --> 00:02:00.420
figure out what they're going to
do and then respond

00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:03.414
appropriately.
So we're going to return to

00:02:03.414 --> 00:02:07.724
both of these lessons today.
Both of these lessons will

00:02:07.724 --> 00:02:11.071
reoccur today.
Now, a lot of today is going to

00:02:11.071 --> 00:02:14.288
be fairly abstract,
so I just want to remind you

00:02:14.288 --> 00:02:17.710
that Game Theory has some real
world relevance.

00:02:17.710 --> 00:02:21.123
Again, still in the interest of
recapping, this particular game

00:02:21.123 --> 00:02:23.050
is called the Prisoners'
Dilemma.

00:02:23.050 --> 00:02:25.290
It's written there,
the Prisoners' Dilemma.

00:02:25.290 --> 00:02:29.720
Notice, it's Prisoners, plural.
And we mentioned some examples

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:31.557
last time.
Let me just reiterate and

00:02:31.557 --> 00:02:34.149
mention some more examples which
are actually written here,

00:02:34.149 --> 00:02:36.160
so they'll find their way into
your notes.

00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:38.541
So, for example,
if you have a joint project

00:02:38.541 --> 00:02:41.089
that you're working on,
perhaps it's a homework

00:02:41.089 --> 00:02:43.445
assignment,
or perhaps it's a video project

00:02:43.445 --> 00:02:45.758
like these guys,
that can turn into a Prisoners'

00:02:45.758 --> 00:02:46.979
Dilemma.
Why?

00:02:46.979 --> 00:02:52.740
Because each individual might
have an incentive to shirk.

00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:56.113
Price competition -- two firms
competing with one another in

00:02:56.113 --> 00:02:59.430
prices -- can have a Prisoners'
Dilemma aspect about it.

00:02:59.430 --> 00:03:01.935
Why?
Because no matter how the other

00:03:01.935 --> 00:03:04.571
firm, your competitor,
prices you might have an

00:03:04.571 --> 00:03:08.016
incentive to undercut them.
If both firms behave that way,

00:03:08.016 --> 00:03:11.008
prices will get driven down
towards marginal cost and

00:03:11.008 --> 00:03:13.850
industry profits will suffer.
In the first case,

00:03:13.850 --> 00:03:16.629
if everyone shirks you end up
with a bad product.

00:03:16.629 --> 00:03:19.356
In the second case,
if both firms undercut each

00:03:19.356 --> 00:03:22.793
other, you end up with low
prices, that's actually good for

00:03:22.793 --> 00:03:26.560
consumers but bad for firms.
Let me mention a third example.

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:29.881
Suppose there's a common
resource out there,

00:03:29.881 --> 00:03:34.129
maybe it's a fish stock or
maybe it's the atmosphere.

00:03:34.129 --> 00:03:36.500
There's a Prisoners' Dilemma
aspect to this too.

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:39.210
You might have an incentive to
over fish.

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:41.558
Why?
Because if the other countries

00:03:41.558 --> 00:03:44.190
with this fish stock--let's say
the fish stock is the

00:03:44.190 --> 00:03:47.430
Atlantic--if the other countries
are going to fish as normal,

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:51.120
you may as well fish as normal
too.

00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:53.455
And if the other countries
aren't going to cut down on

00:03:53.455 --> 00:03:55.437
their fishing,
then you want to catch the fish

00:03:55.437 --> 00:03:57.301
now,
because there aren't going to

00:03:57.301 --> 00:04:00.487
be any there tomorrow.
Another example of this would

00:04:00.487 --> 00:04:03.229
be global warming and carbon
emissions.

00:04:03.229 --> 00:04:06.084
Again, leaving aside the
science, about which I'm sure

00:04:06.084 --> 00:04:08.993
some of you know more than me
here, the issue of carbon

00:04:08.993 --> 00:04:11.039
emissions is a Prisoners'
Dilemma.

00:04:11.039 --> 00:04:15.337
Each of us individually has an
incentive to emit carbons as

00:04:15.337 --> 00:04:17.139
usual.
If everyone else is cutting

00:04:17.139 --> 00:04:19.424
down I don't have too,
and if everyone else does cut

00:04:19.424 --> 00:04:22.135
down I don't have to,
I end up using hot water and

00:04:22.135 --> 00:04:25.716
driving a big car and so on.
In each of these cases we end

00:04:25.716 --> 00:04:29.230
up with a bad outcome,
so this is socially important.

00:04:29.230 --> 00:04:31.978
This is not just some abstract
thing going on in a class in

00:04:31.978 --> 00:04:33.327
Yale.
We need to think about

00:04:33.327 --> 00:04:35.409
solutions to this,
right from the start of the

00:04:35.409 --> 00:04:37.629
class, and we already talked
about something.

00:04:37.629 --> 00:04:41.989
We pointed out,
that this is not just a failure

00:04:41.989 --> 00:04:45.406
of communication.
Communication per se will not

00:04:45.406 --> 00:04:47.470
get you out of a Prisoners'
Dilemma.

00:04:47.470 --> 00:04:50.127
You can talk about it as much
as you like, but as long as

00:04:50.127 --> 00:04:52.926
you're going to go home and
still drive your Hummer and have

00:04:52.926 --> 00:04:55.443
sixteen hot showers a day,
we're still going to have high

00:04:55.443 --> 00:04:57.918
carbon emissions.
You can talk about working hard

00:04:57.918 --> 00:05:01.263
on your joint problem sets,
but as long as you go home and

00:05:01.263 --> 00:05:03.610
you don't work hard,
it doesn't help.

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:05.244
In fact, if the other person is
working hard,

00:05:05.244 --> 00:05:06.990
or is cutting back on their
carbon emissions,

00:05:06.990 --> 00:05:10.047
you have every bit more
incentive to not work hard or to

00:05:10.047 --> 00:05:12.160
keep high carbon emissions
yourself.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:15.188
So we need something more and
the kind of things we can see

00:05:15.188 --> 00:05:17.120
more: we can think about
contracts;

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:19.510
we can think about treaties
between countries;

00:05:19.510 --> 00:05:23.890
we can think about regulation.
All of these things work by

00:05:23.890 --> 00:05:27.520
changing the payoffs.
Not just talking about it,

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:31.561
but actually changing the
outcomes actually and changing

00:05:31.561 --> 00:05:34.500
the payoffs, changing the
incentives.

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:36.651
Another thing we can do,
a very important thing,

00:05:36.651 --> 00:05:39.488
is we can think about changing
the game into a game of repeated

00:05:39.488 --> 00:05:41.639
interaction and seeing how much
that helps,

00:05:41.639 --> 00:05:45.230
and we'll come back and revisit
that later in the class.

00:05:45.230 --> 00:05:48.094
One last thing we can think of
doing but we have to be a bit

00:05:48.094 --> 00:05:50.182
careful here,
is we can think about changing

00:05:50.182 --> 00:05:53.019
the payoffs by education.
I think of that as the "Maoist"

00:05:53.019 --> 00:05:54.693
strategy.
Lock people up in classrooms

00:05:54.693 --> 00:05:56.600
and tell them they should be
better people.

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:58.876
That may or may not work -- I'm
not optimistic -- but at least

00:05:58.876 --> 00:06:03.170
it's the same idea.
We're changing payoffs.

00:06:03.170 --> 00:06:08.709
So that's enough for recap and
I want to move on now.

00:06:08.709 --> 00:06:12.278
And in particular,
we left you hanging at the end

00:06:12.278 --> 00:06:14.613
last time.
We played a game at the very

00:06:14.613 --> 00:06:16.624
end last time,
where each of you chose a

00:06:16.624 --> 00:06:19.718
number -- all of you chose a
number -- and we said the winner

00:06:19.718 --> 00:06:22.760
was going to be the person who
gets closest to two-thirds of

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:25.509
the average in the class.
Now we've figured that out,

00:06:25.509 --> 00:06:27.911
we figured out who the winner
is, and I know that all of you

00:06:27.911 --> 00:06:30.069
have been trying to see if you
won, is that right?

00:06:30.069 --> 00:06:32.170
I'm going to leave you in
suspense.

00:06:32.170 --> 00:06:33.480
I am going to tell you today
who won.

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:35.963
We did figure it out,
and we'll get there,

00:06:35.963 --> 00:06:38.750
but I want to do a little bit
of work first.

00:06:38.750 --> 00:06:40.000
So we're just going to leave it
in suspense.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.868
That'll stop you walking out
early if you want to win the

00:06:46.868 --> 00:06:49.295
prize.
So there's going to be lots of

00:06:49.295 --> 00:06:51.560
times in this class when we get
to play games,

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:54.126
we get to have classroom
discussions and so on,

00:06:54.126 --> 00:06:57.418
but there's going to be some
times when we have to slow down

00:06:57.418 --> 00:07:00.139
and do some work,
and the next twenty minutes are

00:07:00.139 --> 00:07:04.003
going to be that.
So with apologies for being a

00:07:04.003 --> 00:07:09.420
bit more boring for twenty
minutes, let's do something

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:14.234
we'll call formal stuff.
In particular,

00:07:14.234 --> 00:07:21.424
I want to develop and make sure
we all understand,

00:07:21.424 --> 00:07:27.000
what are the ingredients of a
game?

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.139
So in particular,
we need to figure out what

00:07:29.139 --> 00:07:31.079
formally makes something into a
game.

00:07:31.079 --> 00:07:34.819
The formal parts of a game are
this.

00:07:34.819 --> 00:07:40.394
We need players -- and while
we're here let's develop some

00:07:40.394 --> 00:07:43.609
notation.
So the standard notation for

00:07:43.609 --> 00:07:48.269
players, I'm going to use things
like little i and little j.

00:07:48.269 --> 00:07:51.453
So in that numbers game,
the game when all of you wrote

00:07:51.453 --> 00:07:54.636
down a number and handed it in
at the end of last time,

00:07:54.636 --> 00:07:56.960
the players were who?
The players were you.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:08:01.033
You'all were the players.
Useful text and expression

00:08:01.033 --> 00:08:08.526
meaning you plural.
In the numbers game,

00:08:08.526 --> 00:08:20.047
you'all, were the players.
Second ingredient of the game

00:08:20.047 --> 00:08:23.170
are strategies.
(There's a good clue here.

00:08:23.170 --> 00:08:31.711
If I'm writing you should be
writing.) Notation:

00:08:31.711 --> 00:08:40.617
so I'm going to use little
"s_i" to be a

00:08:40.617 --> 00:08:49.996
particular strategy of Player i.
So an example in that game

00:08:49.996 --> 00:08:54.360
might have been choosing the
number 13.

00:08:54.360 --> 00:08:58.628
Everyone understand that?
Now I need to distinguish this

00:08:58.628 --> 00:09:01.870
from the set of possible
strategies of Player I,

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:05.870
so I'm going to use capital
"S_i" to be what?

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:21.210
To be the set of alternatives.
The set of possible strategies

00:09:21.210 --> 00:09:25.996
of Player i.
So in that game we played at

00:09:25.996 --> 00:09:28.081
the end last time,
what were the set of

00:09:28.081 --> 00:09:33.173
strategies?
They were the sets 1,2,

00:09:33.173 --> 00:09:39.309
3, all the way up to 100.
When distinguishing a

00:09:39.309 --> 00:09:42.700
particular strategy from the set
of possible strategies.

00:09:42.700 --> 00:09:45.417
While we're here,
our third notation for

00:09:45.417 --> 00:09:49.250
strategy, I'm going to use
little "s" without an "i,"

00:09:49.250 --> 00:09:59.331
(no subscripts):
little "s" without an "i," to

00:09:59.331 --> 00:10:07.620
mean a particular play of the
game.

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:10.698
So what do I mean by that?
All of you, at the end last

00:10:10.698 --> 00:10:15.139
time, wrote down this number and
handed them in so we had one

00:10:15.139 --> 00:10:19.580
number, one strategy choice for
each person in the class.

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:23.066
So here they are,
here's my collected in,

00:10:23.066 --> 00:10:26.378
sort of strategy choices.
Here's the bundle of bits of

00:10:26.378 --> 00:10:29.488
paper you handed in last time.
This is a particular play of

00:10:29.488 --> 00:10:32.318
the game.
I've got each person's name and

00:10:32.318 --> 00:10:36.042
I've got a number from each
person: a strategy from each

00:10:36.042 --> 00:10:37.890
person.
We actually have it on a

00:10:37.890 --> 00:10:40.328
spreadsheet as well:
so here it is written out on a

00:10:40.328 --> 00:10:42.929
spreadsheet.
Each of your names is on this

00:10:42.929 --> 00:10:45.379
spreadsheet and the number you
chose.

00:10:45.379 --> 00:10:48.075
So that's a particular play of
the game and that has a

00:10:48.075 --> 00:10:53.297
different name.
We sometimes call this "a

00:10:53.297 --> 00:10:57.585
strategy profile."
So in the textbook,

00:10:57.585 --> 00:11:00.719
you'll sometimes see the term a
strategy profile or a strategy

00:11:00.719 --> 00:11:03.059
vector, or a strategy list.
It doesn't really matter.

00:11:03.059 --> 00:11:07.211
What it's saying is one
strategy for each player in the

00:11:07.211 --> 00:11:11.943
game.
So in the numbers game this is

00:11:11.943 --> 00:11:20.470
the spreadsheet -- or an example
of this is the spreadsheet.

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:26.127
(I need to make it so you can
still see that,

00:11:26.127 --> 00:11:31.399
so I'm going to pull down these
boards.

00:11:31.399 --> 00:11:37.722
And let me clean something.) So
you might think we're done

00:11:37.722 --> 00:11:40.710
right?
We've got players.

00:11:40.710 --> 00:11:43.035
We've got the choices they
could make: that's their

00:11:43.035 --> 00:11:45.319
strategy sets.
We've got those individual

00:11:45.319 --> 00:11:47.468
strategies.
And we've got the choices they

00:11:47.468 --> 00:11:49.769
actually did make:
that's the strategy profile.

00:11:49.769 --> 00:11:51.421
Seems like we've got everything
you could possibly want to

00:11:51.421 --> 00:11:54.610
describe in a game.
What are we missing here?

00:11:54.610 --> 00:11:56.830
Shout it out.
"Payoffs."

00:11:56.830 --> 00:12:02.451
We're missing payoffs.
So, to complete the game,

00:12:02.451 --> 00:12:07.224
we need payoffs.
Again, I need notation for

00:12:07.224 --> 00:12:09.347
payoffs.
So in this course,

00:12:09.347 --> 00:12:14.059
I'll try and use "U" for utile,
to be Player i's payoff.

00:12:14.059 --> 00:12:18.644
So "U_i" will depend
on Player 1's choice …

00:12:18.644 --> 00:12:22.063
all the way to Player i's own
choice …

00:12:22.063 --> 00:12:25.250
all the way up to Player N's
choices.

00:12:25.250 --> 00:12:28.560
So Player i's payoff
"U_i," depends on all

00:12:28.560 --> 00:12:31.027
the choices in the class,
in this case,

00:12:31.027 --> 00:12:35.421
including her own choice.
Of course, a shorter way of

00:12:35.421 --> 00:12:40.165
writing that would be
"U_i(s)," it depends

00:12:40.165 --> 00:12:44.323
on the profile.
So in the numbers game what is

00:12:44.323 --> 00:12:46.559
this?
In the numbers game

00:12:46.559 --> 00:12:50.039
"U_i(s)" can be two
things.

00:12:50.039 --> 00:12:56.815
It can be 5 dollars minus your
error in pennies,

00:12:56.815 --> 00:12:59.842
if you won.
I guess it could be something

00:12:59.842 --> 00:13:01.671
if there was a tie,
I won't bother writing that

00:13:01.671 --> 00:13:07.529
now.
And it's going to be 0

00:13:07.529 --> 00:13:13.056
otherwise.
So we've now got all of the

00:13:13.056 --> 00:13:17.515
ingredients of the game:
players, strategies,

00:13:17.515 --> 00:13:20.598
payoffs.
Now we're going to make an

00:13:20.598 --> 00:13:24.460
assumption today and for the
next ten weeks or so;

00:13:24.460 --> 00:13:29.670
so for almost all the class.
We're going to assume that

00:13:29.670 --> 00:13:33.966
these are known.
We're going to assume that

00:13:33.966 --> 00:13:38.153
everybody knows the possible
strategies everyone else could

00:13:38.153 --> 00:13:41.980
choose and everyone knows
everyone else's payoffs.

00:13:41.980 --> 00:13:44.328
Now that's not a very realistic
assumption and we are going to

00:13:44.328 --> 00:13:46.330
come back and challenge it at
the end of semester,

00:13:46.330 --> 00:13:49.725
but this will be complicated
enough to give us a lot of

00:13:49.725 --> 00:13:54.784
material in the next ten weeks.
I need one more piece of

00:13:54.784 --> 00:14:01.500
notation and then we can get
back to having some fun.

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:06.018
So one more piece of notation,
I'm going to write

00:14:06.018 --> 00:14:11.059
"s_-i" to mean what?
It's going to mean a strategy

00:14:11.059 --> 00:14:13.860
choice for everybody except
person "i."

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:16.830
It's going to be useful to have
that notation around.

00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:30.049
So this is a choice for all
except person "i" or Player i.

00:14:30.049 --> 00:14:32.841
So, in particular,
if you're person 1 and then

00:14:32.841 --> 00:14:35.323
"s_-i" would be
"s_2,

00:14:35.323 --> 00:14:37.433
s_3,
s_4" up to

00:14:37.433 --> 00:14:41.280
"s_n" but it wouldn't
include "s_1."

